* Thank you

In this penultimate post we'd like to recap the contributions by our fantastic authors.

So far this year's Go Advent has generated 56k TODO(dfc) unique page views and exists as a perminent resource for the future.

[[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-01-go-1.2][Day 1]] kicked off Go Advent in great style with the announcement of the Go 1.2 release by Andrew Gerrand.

[[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-02-go-1.2-performance-improvements][Day 2]] arrived shortly after bringing news that once again the Go team had pulled another rabbit from their performance hat.

On [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-03-building-a-twelve-factor-app-in-go][day 3]] [[https://twitter.com/kelseyhightower][Kelsey Hightower]] explained how to handle application configuration, [[http://12factor.net/][12 factor app style], in your Go applications.

In their post on [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-04-goconvey][day 4]], [[https://twitter.com/mholt][Matthew Holt]] and [[https://twitter.com/mdwhatcott][Michael Whatcott]] introduced [[https://github.com/smartystreets/goconvey][GoConvey]], their testing framework for Go.

For his post on [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-05-beego][day 5]] [[https://plus.google.com/106856826379042824026][Jiahua Chen]] introduced [[http://beego.me/][beego]] which has recently announced its 1.0 release.

On [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-06-service-discovery-with-etcd][day 6]] [[https://twitter.com/andybons][Andrew Bonventre]] spilt the beans on how [[https://poptip.com/][Poptip]] use [[https://github.com/coreos/etcd][etcd]] to manage service discovery and configuration.

Finishing out the week, James Stewart explained on [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-07-a-router-for-govuk][day 7]] how he used Go to replace the frontend router for the entire `gov.uk` domann.

Heading into the second week, [[https://plus.google.com/+ElliottStoneham/about][Elliott Stoneham]] explained on [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-08-dr-who-and-the-mutant-go-compilers][day 8]] how he used [[http://haxe.org/][haxe]], the Go SSA package and a sonic screwdriver to translate Go code into Javascript.

On [[http://blog.gopheracademy.com/day-09-building-a-weather-app-using-go][day 9]] it was [[https://twitter.com/goinggodotnet][William Kennedy]]'s turn to explain how he launched [[https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/outcast-noaa-radar-hourly/id739808997?mt=8][Outcast]], an iOS applicatoin, using a backend powered entirely by Go.

